title: For Sale:  Springfield M1A, Millett TRS-1 scope, 10 20-Round magazines, AWESOME SHOOTER
postcontent: Manufactured in 2001, seriously upgraded weapon.  Sadlak spring guide, gas piston and unitized cylinder.  Bedded action, USGI stock with stiffened forend.  Bassett Machine quick-release scope mount, holding a Millett TRS-1 4x16-50mm illuminated mildot-bar reticle.  Cheek pad, Harris bipod mounted on custom mounted front stud.  Have original 10-round magazine, plus 1o more 20-round military-issue magazines, all in like-new condition (6 of them have never had rounds put in them).  I'm into this for an honest $3000, no joke.  And as you can see, this is painted in ATACS-AU camouflage.  So how does it shoot???  The typical M1A standard rifle typically delivers 3 MOA as it comes from the factory, using Federal Gold Medal Match ammo, 168-grain BTHP.  The "loaded" version typically delivers 1.5-2 MOA, and the insanely expensive (and heavy) National Match version typically delivers 1-1.5 MOA, if you do your part.  The match versions- while they shoot tighter groups- do it with tighter tolerances, which translates into reduced reliability in "real-world" or SHTF situations...    This started life as a "standard," but shoots like a National Match version.  (And yeah, it's got about ~440 rounds shot through it since new, mostly to verify accuracy and tuning steps.)When you talk about accuracy, a lot of people will shoot a 3-round group, because the probability of getting a "flier" goes up dramatically with a 4 or 5-round group...  But those fliers must be included in the overall average, which would show the rifle is not nearly as accurate as the shooter (or manufacturer) claims.  This goes into statistical analysis, but basically the fewer shots you take, the better you make the gun look, even though it might have bad accuracy.This particular weapon delivered 3 MOA (4 on a bad day), straight out of the box. In the attached pic, you'll see a 7-shout group, at 1.4 MOA using Federal match ammo, in high wind.  That's off the bipod and a sandbag at the back, nothing else.  In other words, this delivers the goods, and THEN some, no tricks.  That translates into hitting man-sized targets consistently out to 700-800 yards, with off-the-shelf ammo.  Further load development should improve that a bit more, if that's your thing...This thing just *shoots,* eats anything you feed it, and is no-BS reliable...  And everyone who sees it thinks it looks REALLY cool.I'm selling it to get something smaller, lighter that I can handle more easily while carrying all my gear.  Questions, text or call at REDACTED.  [Yeah, originally a California #, but I live here in PA now, so there you go....]
